<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="49" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="4.[189,303,1770,1796]" box="[189,303,1770,1796]" pageId="4" pageNumber="49">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,303,1770,1796]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="4" pageNumber="49" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,303,1770,1796]" pageId="4" pageNumber="49">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[188,1399,1816,2019]" pageId="4" pageNumber="49">
This species is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Muir, 1925" authorityName="Muir" authorityYear="1925" box="[514,888,1816,1843]" class="Insecta" family="Cixiidae" genus="Andes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maculifrons">
<emphasis box="[514,738,1816,1842]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="49">Andes maculifrons</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Muir F. A. G." box="[751,888,1816,1843]" pageId="4" pageNumber="49" pagination="201 - 228" refId="ref10020" refString="Muir F. A. G. 1925. The genus Andes Stal (Cixiidae: Homoptera). The Philippine Journal of Science 27 (2): 201 - 228." type="journal article" year="1925">
Muir, 
<quantity box="[829,888,1816,1843]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.8895" pageId="4" pageNumber="49" unit="in" value="1925.0">1925</quantity>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
in appearance, but differs in: (1) ventral margin of periandrium with a belt-shaped process on apical third (ventral margin of periandrium with a triangular process on apical half in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Muir" authorityYear="1925" box="[595,765,1887,1913]" class="Insecta" family="Cixiidae" genus="Andes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maculifrons">
<emphasis box="[595,765,1887,1913]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="49">A. maculifrons</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); (2) endosoma broad, apical margin with two spinose processes (apical margin of endosoma with only one spinose process in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Muir" authorityYear="1925" box="[1034,1206,1922,1948]" class="Insecta" family="Cixiidae" genus="Andes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maculifrons">
<emphasis box="[1034,1206,1922,1948]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="49">A. maculifrons</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); (3) left side of periandrium without a spinose process (base of left side of periandrium with a tiny spinose process in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Muir" authorityYear="1925" box="[190,361,1992,2019]" class="Insecta" family="Cixiidae" genus="Andes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maculifrons">
<emphasis box="[190,361,1992,2019]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="49">A. maculifrons</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
